Testing code not only helps programmers iterate versions based on what works and what doesnt work,
 but it also helps the programmer to experience what the user would experience,which can be very usefil in helping them to identify
and reduce redundancies that may or may not arise during the use of the program, which they might otherwise ignore if they hadnt tested
 it themself. In my code in particular,
I test often when I'm writing code, which helps me to be more thoughtful, and catch errors as I right them,
 rather than having to retroactively go back at the end of the writing and find and debug every little issue
 with the program. It helps me to catch errors before they pile up, and makes debugging a smooth, simple process 
 where I can just fix the bugs one at a time instead of dealing with an infestation at the end of the writing.